<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Computing_and_technology">Computing and technology</span></h2>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/.wiki" title=".wiki">.wiki</a>, a generic top-level domain overseen by ICANN</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/PBworks" title="PBworks">PBworks</a> (formerly PBwiki), a commercial real-time collaborative editing (RTCE) system</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Wiki_software" title="Wiki software">Wiki software</a>, software used to run a wiki website</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Wikimedia_Foundation" title="Wikimedia Foundation">Wikimedia Foundation</a>, a US non-profit charitable organization
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Wikimedia_movement" title="Wikimedia movement">Wikimedia movement</a>, or Wikimedia, the global community of contributors to Wikimedia Foundation projects</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia" title="Wikipedia">Wikipedia</a>, a wiki encyclopedia sometimes referred to as "wiki"</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/WikiWikiWeb" title="WikiWikiWeb">WikiWikiWeb</a>, the original wiki website, and originator of the word "wiki"</li></ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Places">Places</span></h2>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Wiki_Peak" title="Wiki Peak">Wiki Peak</a>, a mountain in Alaska, USA</li></ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="People_with_the_name">People with the name</span></h2>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Wiki_(rapper)" title="Wiki (rapper)">Wiki (rapper)</a>, stage name of Patrick Morales, an American rapper</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Wiki_Baker" title="Wiki Baker">Wiki Baker</a>, vocalist and community worker from New Zealand</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Wiki_Gonz%C3%A1lez" title="Wiki González">Wiki González</a>, Major League baseball player</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Wieke_Hoogzaad" title="Wieke Hoogzaad">Wieke Hoogzaad</a> (nicknamed <i>Wiki de Viking</i>), Dutch triathlete</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ruben_Wiki" title="Ruben Wiki">Ruben Wiki</a>, New Zealand rugby league footballer</li></ul>
<h2><span id="Arts.2C_entertainment.2C_and_media"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Arts,_entertainment,_and_media">Arts, entertainment, and media</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Fictional_entities">Fictional entities</span></h3>
<ul><li>W1K1, pronounced "wiki", a mini-robot from the 1970s Filmation sci-fi show <i><a href="/wiki/Jason_of_Star_Command" title="Jason of Star Command">Jason of Star Command</a></i></li>
<li>Wiki, a sidekick character in the video game <i><a href="/wiki/Zack_%26_Wiki:_Quest_for_Barbaros%27_Treasure" title="Zack &amp; Wiki: Quest for Barbaros&#39; Treasure">Zack &amp; Wiki: Quest for Barbaros' Treasure</a></i></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Vicky_the_Viking" title="Vicky the Viking">Vicky the Viking</a> (also <i>Wikki</i> or <i>Wickie</i>), a 1970s animated cartoon character</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Wiki_Dankowska" class="mw-redirect" title="Wiki Dankowska">Wiki Dankowska</a>, a fictional character in the British television show <i>Coronation Street</i></li></ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Music">Music</span></h3>
<ul><li>"Jam on Revenge (the Wikki-Wikki Song)", a 1983 single by the band <a href="/wiki/Newcleus" title="Newcleus">Newcleus</a>
<ul><li>"Wiki wiki", a phrase meant to simulate a DJ scratching a turntable, used by Newcleus in several songs as well as Will Smith's <a href="/wiki/Wild_Wild_West_(Will_Smith_song)" title="Wild Wild West (Will Smith song)">"Wild Wild West"</a>, among others</li></ul></li></ul>
<h3><span id="Other_uses_in_arts.2C_entertainment.2C_and_media"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Other_uses_in_arts,_entertainment,_and_media">Other uses in arts, entertainment, and media</span></h3>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/WIKI_(FM)" title="WIKI (FM)">WIKI (FM)</a> a country music radio station in Carrollton, Kentucky, United States</li>
<li>"Wiki-wiki", a story (and title character) written by the title character of Jack London's novel <i><a href="/wiki/Martin_Eden" title="Martin Eden">Martin Eden</a></i></li></ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Other_uses">Other uses</span></h2>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Wiki_wiki_dollar" title="Wiki wiki dollar">Wiki wiki dollar</a>, a 1960s gasoline give-away promotion</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Wiki_Wiki_Shuttle" title="Wiki Wiki Shuttle">Wiki Wiki Shuttle</a>, a Hawaiian airport bus system</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/WikiLeaks" title="WikiLeaks">WikiLeaks</a>, an international non-profit organisation that publishes secret information, news leaks, and classified media provided by anonymous sources</li></ul>

class="infobox-label">Introduced</th><td class="infobox-data">May 26, 2014 (general public)</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label"><a href="/wiki/Top-level_domain" title="Top-level <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1033289096">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}</style><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable selfref">"w.wiki" redirects here. For Wikimedia projects' URL shortener, see <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:URLShortener" title="Wikipedia:URLShortener">Wikipedia:URLShortener</a>.</div>
<p><b>.wiki</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Top-level_domain" title="Top-level domain">top-level domain</a> name.  It was proposed in <a href="/wiki/ICANN" title="ICANN">ICANN</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Generic_top-level_domain#New_top-level_domains" title="Generic top-level domain">New generic top-level domain (gTLD) Program</a>, and became available to the general public on May 26, 2014. <a href="/wiki/Top_Level_Design" title="Top Level Design">Top Level Design</a> is the <a href="/wiki/Domain_name_registry" title="Domain name registry">domain name registry</a> for the string.
</p>
<div id="toc" class="toc" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading"><input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" /><div class="toctitle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><h2 id="mw-toc-heading">Contents</h2><span class="toctogglespan"><label class="toctogglelabel" for="toctogglecheckbox"></label></span></div>

<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-5"><a href="#External_links"><span class="tocnumber">5</span> <span class="toctext">External links</span></a></li>
</ul>
</div>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=.wiki&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In June 2012, Top Level Design submitted an application to ICANN for the .wiki gTLD.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> On November 7, 2013, <a href="/wiki/ICANN" title="ICANN">ICANN</a> and Top Level Design entered into a "Registry Agreement", officially allowing the company to operate as the registry for .wiki.<sup id="cite_ref-WRA_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WRA-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Following the acquisition, <a href="/wiki/Ray_King_(entrepreneur)" title="Ray King (entrepreneur)">Ray King</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chief_executive_officer" title="Chief executive officer">CEO</a> of Top Level Design, stated many people "from within [the domain] industry tell me that .wiki is their dark horse for a successful [g]TLD," because ".wiki" describes the site format. "So, when I go to craftbeer.wiki, I can expect a vibrant site with passionate folks discussing all things relevant to brewing beer. This is not the case with craftbeer.com or craftbeer.guru, where you could be accessing a storefront, a blog, a brewery tourguide or any number of things."<sup id="cite_ref-Levine_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Levine-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In January 2014, .wiki was named one of the "Top 10 gTLDs to Watch in 2014" by ClickZ for having the "potential to provide great secure, shared workspaces for companies large and small".<sup id="cite_ref-Wolfe_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wolfe-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The application was delegated to the <a href="/wiki/DNS_root_zone" title="DNS root zone">DNS root zone</a> on February 19, 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> By mid-March, Top Level Design had signed agreements with more than 120 <a href="/wiki/Domain_name_registrar" title="Domain name registrar">domain name registrars</a> to retail .wiki names.<sup id="cite_ref-Apple_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Apple-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> It was announced in May that the <a href="/wiki/Wikimedia_Foundation" title="Wikimedia Foundation">Wikimedia Foundation</a>, the non-profit organization mostly known for hosting <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia" title="Wikipedia">Wikipedia</a>, would use "w.wiki" as a <a href="/wiki/URL_shortening" title="URL shortening">URL shortener</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Wikipedia_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wikipedia-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> The Foundation also endorsed Top Level Design's proposal to ICANN's Registry Services Evaluation Process to unblock 179 two-letter strings representing language codes (all two-character strings are blocked under ICANN's standard Registry Agreement).<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Three_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Three-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Collaborate_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Collaborate-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>.wiki domain registrations were available to only trademark holders until May 5; they became available to the general public on May 26, 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Haggerty_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Haggerty-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> According to Domain Name Wire, more than 3,000 .wiki domains were registered on the first day of general availability.<sup id="cite_ref-Collaborate_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Collaborate-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As part of the gTLD's launch, Top Level Design and <a href="/wiki/YouGov" title="YouGov">YouGov</a> released a report which concluded that nearly half of consumers in the United Kingdom and the United States have "little to no opportunity" to collaborate with their favorite brands online, and prefer brands that make online collaboration available to them.<sup id="cite_ref-Haggerty_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Haggerty-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> An additional fifteen percent of U.K. consumers wished they could collaborate with their favorite brands on future products.<sup id="cite_ref-Jenkins_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jenkins-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Finally, the report said nearly a quarter of U.K. and U.S. consumers want companies to solicit their ideas for future products and would contribute to a branded <a href="/wiki/Wiki" title="Wiki">wiki</a> "if they could make a difference to an organisation, brand, service or community they feel passionately about".<sup id="cite_ref-Haggerty_12-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Haggerty-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Mehta_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mehta-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> King acknowledged his interest in promoting collaboration between companies and consumers, given the collaborative nature of wikis and Top Level Design's acquisition of the .wiki gTLD.<sup id="cite_ref-Mehta_14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mehta-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> He said of the study's findings:
</p>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r996844942">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class="templatequote"><p>Consumers and businesses alike have long recognised the power and potential that the internet has to improve the products and services businesses offer, creating a better two-way dialogue between customers and their favourite brands... In reality, this research shows that most consumers feel that the opportunity to collaborate with most companies they love still doesn't yet exist.<sup id="cite_ref-Haggerty_12-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Haggerty-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Jenkins_13-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jenkins-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>In July 2015, .wiki was included in a list of the "Top 20 Best New gTLDs Based on Quality", based on data gathered from more than 20,000 developed websites on new gTLD domains, as part of Globe Runner's New gTLD SEO Power Rankings Index.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Purpose">Purpose</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=.wiki&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Purpose">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In its 2012 application, Top Level Design stated that the purpose of the .wiki top-level domain would be "to create a designated Internet space for wikis. This [gTLD] will clearly identify wikis from among the millions of other websites populating the Internet, and allow Internet users to easily find wikis relevant to their interests. Wiki websites are a growing phenomenon on the Internet and an innovative, easy-to-use peer-production method of creating and presenting information. They are generally open and editable and often community-driven; furthermore, individual wikis and the wiki platform are in constant flux in much the same way that the Internet as a whole is in flux. Wikis, like the broader Internet, are repositories of information that depend on each individual user to create value; they are meeting points and revolutionary ways to share ideas and knowledge; and they are both set to be expanded through the implementation of ICANN's New gTLD Program, and a .wiki [gTLD] specifically. We believe a .wiki [gTLD] is an intuitive and necessary addition to the collection of new gTLDs to be added as a result of the New gTLD Program."<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=.wiki&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1072126029">.mw-parser-output .portalbox{float:right;padding:0}.mw-parser-output .portalborder{border:solid #aaa 1px}.mw-parser-output .portalbox.tleft{margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0}.mw-parser-output .portalbox.tright{margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 1em}.mw-parser-output .portalbox>ul{display:table;box-sizing:border-box;max-width:175px;font-size:85%;line-height:110%;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold}.mw-parser-output .portalborder>ul{padding:0.1em;background:#f9f9f9}.mw-parser-output .portalbox>ul>li{display:table-row}.mw-parser-output .portalbox>ul>li>span:first-child{display:table-cell;padding:0.2em;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center}.mw-parser-output .portalbox>ul>li>span:last-child{display:table-cell;padding:0.2em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em;vertical-align:middle}</style><div role="navigation" aria-label="Portals" class="noprint plainlist portalbox portalborder tright">

<nav id="p-coll-print_export" class="mw-portlet mw-portlet-coll-print_export vector-menu vector-menu-portal portal" aria-labelledby="p-coll-print_export-label" role="navigation"

	</label>

****** Response Body For Transaction With Id 298 ******
{"type":"standard","title":"Top-level domain","displaytitle":"Top-level domain","namespace":{"id":0,"text":""},"wikibase_item":"Q14296","titles":{"canonical":"Top-level_domain","normalized":"Top-level domain","display":"Top-level domain"},"pageid":31115,"lang":"en","dir":"ltr","revision":"1075218031","tid":"b9f58250-a16b-11ec-abd7-651d06055314","timestamp":"2022-03-04T15:25:39Z","description":"Domain at the highest level of the DNS hierarchy","description_source":"local","content_urls":{"desktop":{"page":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top-level_domain","revisions":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top-level_domain?action=history","edit":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top-level_domain?action=edit","talk":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Top-level_domain"},"mobile":{"page":"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top-level_domain","revisions":"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:History/Top-level_domain","edit":"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top-level_domain?action=edit","talk":"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Top-level_domain"}},"extract":"A top-level domain (TLD) is one of the domains at the highest level in the hierarchical Domain Name System of the Internet after the root domain. The top-level domain names are installed in the root zone of the name space. For all domains in lower levels, it is the last part of the domain name, that is, the last non empty label of a fully qualified domain name. For example, in the domain name www.example.com., the top-level domain is com. Responsibility for management of most top-level domains is delegated to specific organizations by the ICANN, an Internet multi-stakeholder community, which operates the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA), and is in charge of maintaining the DNS root zone.","extract_html":"<p>A <b>top-level domain</b> (<b>TLD</b>) is one of the domains at the highest level in the hierarchical Domain Name System of the Internet after the root domain. The top-level domain names are installed in the root zone of the name space. For all domains in lower levels, it is the last part of the domain name, that is, the last non empty label of a fully qualified domain name. For example, in the domain name www.example.com., the top-level domain is com. Responsibility for management of most top-level domains is delegated to specific organizations by the ICANN, an Internet multi-stakeholder community, which operates the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA), and is in charge of maintaining the DNS root zone.</p>"}

	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading mw-first-heading">Top-level domain</h1>
	<div id="bodyContent" class="vector-body">
		<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
		<div id="contentSub"></div>
		<div id="contentSub2"></div>
		
		<div id="jump-to-nav"></div>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation</a>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#searchInput">Jump to search</a>
		<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content mw-content-ltr" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">Domain at the highest level of the DNS hierarchy</div>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1033289096">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}</style><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">"TLD" and "TLDN" redirect here. For Temporary Location Directory Number, see <a href="/wiki/Mobile_Station_Roaming_Number" title="Mobile Station Roaming Number">Mobile Station Roaming Number</a>. For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/TLD_(disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig" title="TLD (disambiguation)">TLD (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Country_code_top-level_domain" title="Country code top-level domain">Country code top-level domain</a></div>
<p class="mw-empty-elt">
</p>

<td>Internationalized country-code
</td>
<td>THNIC<sup id="cite_ref-IANA.xn--o3cw4h_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IANA.xn--o3cw4h-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>A <b>top-level domain</b> (<b>TLD</b>) is one of the <a href="/wiki/Domain_name" title="Domain name">domains</a> at the highest level in the hierarchical <a href="/wiki/Domain_Name_System" title="Domain Name System">Domain Name System</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a> after the root domain.<sup id="cite_ref-rfc1591_2011_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rfc1591_2011-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> The top-level domain names are installed in the <a href="/wiki/DNS_root_zone" title="DNS root zone">root zone</a> of the name space. For all domains in lower levels, it is the last part of the <a href="/wiki/Domain_name" title="Domain name">domain name</a>, that is, the last non empty label of a <a href="/wiki/Fully_qualified_domain_name" title="Fully qualified domain name">fully qualified domain name</a>. For example, in the domain name <a href="/wiki/Example.com" title="Example.com">www.example.com.</a>, the top-level domain is <a href="/wiki/.com" title=".com">com</a>. Responsibility for management of most top-level domains is delegated to specific organizations by the <a href="/wiki/ICANN" title="ICANN">ICANN</a>, an Internet multi-stakeholder community, which operates the <a href="/wiki/Internet_Assigned_Numbers_Authority" title="Internet Assigned Numbers Authority">Internet Assigned Numbers Authority</a> (IANA), and is in charge of maintaining the <a href="/wiki/DNS_root_zone" title="DNS root zone">DNS root zone</a>.
</p>
<div id="toc" class="toc" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading"><input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" /><div class="toctitle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><h2 id="mw-toc-heading">Contents</h2><span class="toctogglespan"><label class="toctogglelabel" for="toctogglecheckbox"></label></span></div>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Originally, the top-level domain space was organized into three main groups: <i>Countries</i>, <i>Categories</i>, and <i>Multiorganizations</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-rfc920_2011_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rfc920_2011-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> An additional <i>temporary</i> group consisted of only the initial DNS domain, <a href="/wiki/.arpa" title=".arpa">arpa</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> and was intended for transitional purposes toward the stabilization of the domain name system.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Types">Types</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Types">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>As of 2015,<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup> IANA distinguishes the following groups of top-level domains:<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href="#Infrastructure_domain">Infrastructure top-level domain</a> (ARPA): This group consists of one domain, the <a href="/wiki/.arpa" title=".arpa">Address and Routing Parameter Area</a>. It is managed by IANA on behalf of the <a href="/wiki/Internet_Engineering_Task_Force" title="Internet Engineering Task Force">Internet Engineering Task Force</a> for various purposes specified in the <a href="/wiki/Request_for_Comments" title="Request for Comments">Request for Comments</a> publications.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Generic_top-level_domain" title="Generic top-level domain">Generic top-level domains</a> (gTLD): Top-level domains with three or more characters</li>
<li>Generic restricted top-level domains (grTLD): These domains are managed under official ICANN accredited registrars.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sponsored_top-level_domain" title="Sponsored top-level domain">Sponsored top-level domains</a> (sTLD): These domains are proposed and sponsored by private agencies or organizations that establish and enforce rules restricting the eligibility to use the TLD. Use is based on community theme concepts; these domains are managed under official ICANN accredited registrars.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Country_code_top-level_domain" title="Country code top-level domain">country-code top-level domains</a> (ccTLD): Two-letter domains established for <a href="/wiki/Country" title="Country">countries</a> or <a href="/wiki/List_of_dependent_territories" class="mw-redirect" title="List of dependent territories">territories</a>. With some historical exceptions, the code for any territory is the same as its two-letter <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166" title="ISO 3166">ISO 3166</a> code.
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Internationalized_country_code_top-level_domain" title="Internationalized country code top-level domain">Internationalized country code top-level domains</a> (IDN ccTLD): ccTLDs in non-Latin character sets (e.g., Arabic, Cyrillic, Greek, Hebrew, or Chinese).</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/.test" title=".test">Test top-level domains</a> (tTLD): These domains were installed under <a href="/wiki/.test" title=".test">.test</a> for testing purposes in the IDN development process; these domains are not present in the root zone.</li></ul>
<p>Countries are designated in the Domain Name System by their <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166-1_alpha-2" title="ISO 3166-1 alpha-2">two-letter ISO country code</a>;<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> there are exceptions, however (e.g., <a href="/wiki/.uk" title=".uk">.uk</a>). This group of domains is therefore commonly known as <a href="/wiki/Country-code_top-level_domain" class="mw-redirect" title="Country-code top-level domain">country-code top-level domains</a> (ccTLD). Since 2009, countries with non–Latin-based scripts may apply for <a href="/wiki/Internationalized_country_code_top-level_domain" title="Internationalized country code top-level domain">internationalized country code top-level domain</a> names, which are displayed in end-user applications in their language-native script or alphabet, but use a <a href="/wiki/Punycode" title="Punycode">Punycode</a>-translated ASCII domain name in the Domain Name System.
</p><p>Generic top-level domains (formerly <i>categories</i>) initially consisted of <a href="/wiki/.gov" title=".gov">gov</a>, <a href="/wiki/.edu" title=".edu">edu</a>, <a href="/wiki/.com" title=".com">com</a>, <a href="/wiki/.mil" title=".mil">mil</a>, <a href="/wiki/.org" title=".org">org</a>, and <a href="/wiki/.net" title=".net">net</a>.  More generic TLDs have been added, such as <a href="/wiki/.info" title=".info">info</a>.
</p><p>The authoritative <a href="/wiki/List_of_Internet_top-level_domains" title="List of Internet top-level domains">list of current TLDs</a> in the root zone is published at the IANA website at <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.iana.org/domains/root/db/">https://www.iana.org/domains/root/db/</a>.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Internationalized_country_code_TLDs">Internationalized country code TLDs</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Internationalized country code TLDs">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>An <a href="/wiki/Internationalized_country_code_top-level_domain" title="Internationalized country code top-level domain">internationalized country code top-level domain</a> (IDN ccTLD) is a top-level domain with a specially encoded domain name that is displayed in an end user application, such as a <a href="/wiki/Web_browser" title="Web browser">web browser</a>, in its language-native script or <a href="/wiki/Alphabet" title="Alphabet">alphabet</a> (such as the <a href="/wiki/Arabic_alphabet" title="Arabic alphabet">Arabic alphabet</a>), or a non-alphabetic <a href="/wiki/Writing_system" title="Writing system">writing system</a> (such as <a href="/wiki/Chinese_character" class="mw-redirect" title="Chinese character">Chinese characters</a>). IDN ccTLDs are an application of the <a href="/wiki/Internationalized_domain_name" title="Internationalized domain name">internationalized domain name</a> (IDN) system to top-level Internet domains assigned to countries, or independent geographic regions.
</p><p>ICANN started to accept applications for IDN ccTLDs in November 2009,<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> and installed the first set into the Domain Names System in May 2010. The first set was a group of Arabic names for the countries of Egypt, Saudi Arabia, and the United Arab Emirates. By May 2010, 21 countries had submitted applications to ICANN, representing 11 scripts.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Infrastructure_domain">Infrastructure domain</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Infrastructure domain">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<table class="box-More_citations_needed plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td class="mbox-image"><div style="width:52px"><a href="/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png" decoding="async" width="50" height="39" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="399" /></a></div></td><td class="mbox-text"><div class="mbox-text-span">This section <b>needs additional citations for <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability">verification</a></b>.<span class="hide-when-compact"> Please help <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit">improve this article</a> by <a href="/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners" title="Help:Referencing for beginners">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.<br /><small><span class="plainlinks"><i>Find sources:</i>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?as_eq=wikipedia&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22">"Top-level domain"</a>&#160;–&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbm=nws&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22+-wikipedia&amp;tbs=ar:1">news</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22&amp;tbs=bkt:s&amp;tbm=bks">newspapers</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbs=bks:1&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22+-wikipedia">books</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22Top-level+domain%22">scholar</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Top-level+domain%22&amp;acc=on&amp;wc=on">JSTOR</a></span></small></span>  <span class="date-container"><i>(<span class="date">December 2018</span>)</i></span><span class="hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a href="/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title="Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The domain <a href="/wiki/.arpa" title=".arpa">arpa</a> was the first Internet top-level domain. It was intended to be used only temporarily, aiding in the transition of traditional ARPANET host names to the domain name system. However, after it had been used for <a href="/wiki/Reverse_DNS_lookup" title="Reverse DNS lookup">reverse DNS lookup</a>, it was found impractical to retire it, and is used today exclusively for Internet infrastructure purposes such as in-addr.arpa for <a href="/wiki/IPv4" title="IPv4">IPv4</a> and ip6.arpa for IPv6 reverse DNS resolution, uri.arpa and urn.arpa for the <a href="/wiki/Dynamic_Delegation_Discovery_System" title="Dynamic Delegation Discovery System">Dynamic Delegation Discovery System</a>, and e164.arpa for <a href="/wiki/Telephone_number_mapping" title="Telephone number mapping">telephone number mapping</a> based on <a href="/wiki/NAPTR_record" title="NAPTR record">NAPTR DNS records</a>. For historical reasons, <a href="/wiki/.arpa" title=".arpa">arpa</a> is sometimes considered to be a generic top-level domain.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Reserved_domains">Reserved domains</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Reserved domains">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>A set of domain names is reserved<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> by the Internet Engineering Task Force as <a href="/wiki/Special-use_domain_name" title="Special-use domain name">special-use domain names</a> per authority of Request for Comments (RFC) 6761. The practice originated in RFC 1597 for reserved address allocations in 1994, and reserved top-level domains in RFC 2606 of 1999. RFC 6761 reserves the following four top-level domain names to avoid confusion and conflict.<sup id="cite_ref-rfc_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rfc-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> Any such reserved usage of those TLDs should not occur in production networks that utilize the global domain name system:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/.example" title=".example">example</a>: reserved for use in examples</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/.invalid" title=".invalid">invalid</a>: reserved for use in invalid domain names</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/.localhost" title=".localhost">localhost</a>: reserved to avoid conflict with the traditional use of <a href="/wiki/Localhost" title="Localhost">localhost</a> as a hostname</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/.test" title=".test">test</a>: reserved for use in tests</li></ul>
<p>RFC 6762 reserves the use of <a href="/wiki/.local" title=".local">.local</a> for link-local host names that can be resolved via the <a href="/wiki/Multicast_DNS" title="Multicast DNS">Multicast DNS</a> name resolution protocol.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>RFC 7686 reserves the use of <a href="/wiki/.onion" title=".onion">.onion</a> for the self-authenticating names of <a href="/wiki/Tor_(network)" title="Tor (network)">Tor</a> <a href="/wiki/Onion_services" class="mw-redirect" title="Onion services">onion services</a>. These names can only be resolved by a Tor client because of the use of <a href="/wiki/Onion_routing" title="Onion routing">onion routing</a> to protect the anonymity of users.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Internet-Draft <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-wkumari-dnsop-internal-00">draft-wkumari-dnsop-internal-00</a> proposes reserving the use of .internal for "names which do not have meaning in the global context but do have meaning in a context internal to their network", and for which the RFC 6761 reserved names are semantically inappropriate.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Historical_domains">Historical domains</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Historical domains">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<table class="box-More_citations_needed plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td class="mbox-image"><div style="width:52px"><a href="/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png" decoding="async" width="50" height="39" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="399" /></a></div></td><td class="mbox-text"><div class="mbox-text-span">This section <b>needs additional citations for <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability">verification</a></b>.<span class="hide-when-compact"> Please help <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit">improve this article</a> by <a href="/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners" title="Help:Referencing for beginners">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.<br /><small><span class="plainlinks"><i>Find sources:</i>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?as_eq=wikipedia&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22">"Top-level domain"</a>&#160;–&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbm=nws&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22+-wikipedia&amp;tbs=ar:1">news</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22&amp;tbs=bkt:s&amp;tbm=bks">newspapers</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbs=bks:1&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22+-wikipedia">books</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22Top-level+domain%22">scholar</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Top-level+domain%22&amp;acc=on&amp;wc=on">JSTOR</a></span></small></span>  <span class="date-container"><i>(<span class="date">December 2018</span>)</i></span><span class="hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a href="/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title="Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>In the late 1980s, <a href="/wiki/InterNIC" title="InterNIC">InterNIC</a> created the <a href="/wiki/.nato" title=".nato">nato</a> domain for use by <a href="/wiki/NATO" title="NATO">NATO</a>.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (November 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> NATO considered none of the then-existing TLDs as adequately reflecting their status as an <a href="/wiki/International_organization" title="International organization">international organization</a>. Soon after this addition, however, InterNIC also created the <a href="/wiki/.int" title=".int">int</a> TLD for the use by international organizations in general, and persuaded NATO to use the second level domain <i>nato.int</i> instead. The <i>nato</i> TLD, no longer used, was finally removed in July 1996.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (November 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>Other historical TLDs are <a href="/wiki/.cs" title=".cs">cs</a> for <a href="/wiki/Czechoslovakia" title="Czechoslovakia">Czechoslovakia</a> (now using <a href="/wiki/.cz" title=".cz">cz</a> for <a href="/wiki/Czech_Republic" title="Czech Republic">Czech Republic</a> and <a href="/wiki/.sk" title=".sk">sk</a> for <a href="/wiki/Slovakia" title="Slovakia">Slovakia</a>), <a href="/wiki/.dd" title=".dd">dd</a> for <a href="/wiki/East_Germany" title="East Germany">East Germany</a> (using <a href="/wiki/.de" title=".de">de</a> after <a href="/wiki/Reunification_of_Germany" class="mw-redirect" title="Reunification of Germany">reunification of Germany</a>), <a href="/wiki/.yu" title=".yu">yu</a> for <a href="/wiki/Socialist_Federal_Republic_of_Yugoslavia" title="Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia">SFR Yugoslavia</a> and <a href="/wiki/Serbia_and_Montenegro" title="Serbia and Montenegro">Serbia and Montenegro</a> (now using <a href="/wiki/.ba" title=".ba">ba</a> for <a href="/wiki/Bosnia_and_Herzegovina" title="Bosnia and Herzegovina">Bosnia and Herzegovina</a>, <a href="/wiki/.hr" title=".hr">hr</a> for <a href="/wiki/Croatia" title="Croatia">Croatia</a>, <a href="/wiki/.me" title=".me">me</a> for <a href="/wiki/Montenegro" title="Montenegro">Montenegro</a>, <a href="/wiki/.mk" title=".mk">mk</a> for <a href="/wiki/North_Macedonia" title="North Macedonia">North Macedonia</a>, <a href="/wiki/.rs" title=".rs">rs</a> for <a href="/wiki/Serbia" title="Serbia">Serbia</a> and <a href="/wiki/.si" title=".si">si</a> for <a href="/wiki/Slovenia" title="Slovenia">Slovenia</a>), and <a href="/wiki/.zr" title=".zr">zr</a> for <a href="/wiki/Zaire" title="Zaire">Zaire</a> (now <a href="/wiki/.cd" title=".cd">cd</a> for the <a href="/wiki/Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo" title="Democratic Republic of the Congo">Democratic Republic of the Congo</a>). In contrast to these, the TLD <a href="/wiki/.su" title=".su">su</a> has remained active despite the demise of the <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union">Soviet Union</a> that it represents. Under the chairmanship of <a href="/wiki/Nigel_Roberts" title="Nigel Roberts">Nigel Roberts</a>, <a href="/wiki/ICANN" title="ICANN">ICANN</a>'s <a href="/wiki/CcNSO" class="mw-redirect" title="CcNSO">ccNSO</a> is working on a policy for retirement of <a href="/wiki/CcTLD" class="mw-redirect" title="CcTLD">ccTLDs</a> that have been removed from <a href="/wiki/ISO_3166" title="ISO 3166">ISO 3166</a>.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Proposed_domains">Proposed domains</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Proposed domains">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Proposed_top-level_domain" title="Proposed top-level domain">Proposed top-level domain</a></div>
<p>Around late 2000, <a href="/wiki/ICANN" title="ICANN">ICANN</a> discussed and finally introduced<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/.aero" title=".aero">aero</a>, <a href="/wiki/.biz" title=".biz">biz</a>, <a href="/wiki/.coop" title=".coop">coop</a>, <a href="/wiki/.info" title=".info">info</a>, <a href="/wiki/.museum" title=".museum">museum</a>, <a href="/wiki/.name" title=".name">name</a>, and <a href="/wiki/.pro" title=".pro">pro</a> TLDs. Site owners argued that a similar TLD should be made available for adult and pornographic websites to settle the dispute of obscene content on the Internet, to address the responsibility of US service providers under the US <a href="/wiki/Communications_Decency_Act" title="Communications Decency Act">Communications Decency Act</a> of 1996.  Several options were proposed including <i>xxx</i>, <i>sex</i> and <i>adult</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/.xxx" title=".xxx">xxx</a> top-level domain eventually went live in 2011.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>An older proposal consisted of seven new gTLDs: arts, firm, <a href="/wiki/.info" title=".info">info</a>, nom, rec, <a href="/wiki/.shop" title=".shop">shop</a>, and <a href="/wiki/.web" title=".web">web</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> Later <a href="/wiki/.biz" title=".biz">biz</a>, <a href="/wiki/.info" title=".info">info</a>, <a href="/wiki/.museum" title=".museum">museum</a>, and <a href="/wiki/.name" title=".name">name</a> covered most of these old proposals.
</p><p>During the 32nd International Public ICANN Meeting in Paris in 2008, ICANN started a new process of TLD naming policy to take a "significant step forward on the introduction of new generic top-level domains".<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> This program envisioned the availability of many new or already proposed domains, as well as a new application and implementation process.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> Observers believed that the new rules could result in hundreds of new gTLDs being registered.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 13 June 2012, <a href="/wiki/ICANN" title="ICANN">ICANN</a> announced nearly 2,000 applications for top-level domains, which began installation throughout 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> The first seven – <i>bike</i>, <i>clothing</i>, <i>guru</i>, <i>holdings</i>, <i>plumbing</i>, <i>singles</i>, and <i>ventures</i> – were released in 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Rejected_domains">Rejected domains</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Rejected domains">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>ICANN rejected several proposed domains to include <a href="/wiki/.home" title=".home">home</a> and <a href="/wiki/.corp" title=".corp">corp</a> due to conflicts regarding gTLDs that are in use in internal networks.
</p><p>Investigation into the conflicts was conducted at ICANN's request by <a href="/w/index.php?title=Interisle_Consulting&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Interisle Consulting (page does not exist)">Interisle Consulting</a>. The resulting report was to become known as the Name Collision<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> issue, which was first reported at ICANN 47.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Dotless_domains">Dotless domains</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Dotless domains">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:DNS_schema.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/DNS_schema.svg/220px-DNS_schema.svg.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="122" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/DNS_schema.svg/330px-DNS_schema.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/DNS_schema.svg/440px-DNS_schema.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1073" data-file-height="596" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:DNS_schema.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i><a href="/wiki/.org" title=".org">org</a>[.]</i> is a node in the DNS tree, just like <i>wikipedia.[org.]</i> and <i>en.[wikipedia.org.]</i>. As such, it has its own <a href="/wiki/DNS_record" class="mw-redirect" title="DNS record">DNS records</a></div></div></div>
<p>Due to the structure of <a href="/wiki/DNS" class="mw-redirect" title="DNS">DNS</a>, each node in the tree has its own collection of <a href="/wiki/DNS_record" class="mw-redirect" title="DNS record">records</a>, and since top-level domains are nodes in DNS, they have records of their own. For example, querying <i>org</i> itself (with a tool such as <a href="/wiki/Dig_(command)" title="Dig (command)">dig</a>, <a href="/wiki/Host_(Unix)" title="Host (Unix)">host</a> or <a href="/wiki/Nslookup" title="Nslookup">nslookup</a>) returns information on its <a href="/wiki/Nameserver" class="mw-redirect" title="Nameserver">nameservers</a>:
</p>
<pre style="font-size:85%">QUESTION
org. IN ANY
ANSWER
org. 21599 IN NS a0.org.afilias-nst.info.
org. 21599 IN NS a2.org.afilias-nst.info.
org. 21599 IN NS b0.org.afilias-nst.org.
org. 21599 IN NS b2.org.afilias-nst.org.
[…]
</pre>
<p><i>Dotless domains</i> are top-level domains that take advantage of that fact, and implement <a href="/wiki/A_record" class="mw-redirect" title="A record">A</a>, <a href="/wiki/AAAA_record" class="mw-redirect" title="AAAA record">AAAA</a> or <a href="/wiki/MX_record" title="MX record">MX</a> DNS records to serve webpages or allow incoming email directly on a TLD – for example, a webpage hosted on <i>http://example/</i>, or an email address <i>user@example</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-dotless-icann_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dotless-icann-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><a href="/wiki/ICANN" title="ICANN">ICANN</a> and <a href="/wiki/Internet_Architecture_Board" title="Internet Architecture Board">IAB</a> have spoken out against the practice, classifying it as a security risk among other concerns.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> ICANN's Security and Stability Advisory Committee (SSAC) additionally claims that <a href="/wiki/SMTP" class="mw-redirect" title="SMTP">SMTP</a> "requires at least two labels in the <a href="/wiki/FQDN" class="mw-redirect" title="FQDN">FQDN</a> of a mail address" and, as such, mail servers would reject emails to addresses with dotless domains.<sup id="cite_ref-dotless-icann_33-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dotless-icann-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>ICANN has also published a resolution in 2013 that prohibits the creation of dotless domains on <a href="/wiki/GTLD" class="mw-redirect" title="GTLD">gTLDs</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/CcTLD" class="mw-redirect" title="CcTLD">ccTLDs</a>, however, fall largely under their respective country's <a href="/wiki/Jurisdiction" title="Jurisdiction">jurisdiction</a>, and not under ICANN's. Because of this, there have been many examples of dotless domains on ccTLDs in spite of ICANN's vocal opposition.
</p><p>As of August 2021, that is the case of <a href="/wiki/Anguilla" title="Anguilla">Anguilla</a>'s <a href="/wiki/.ai" title=".ai">.ai</a>, online at <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://ai./">http://ai./</a> (as a mirror of <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://offshore.ai/">http://offshore.ai/</a>), and of <a href="/wiki/Uzbekistan" title="Uzbekistan">Uzbekistan</a>'s <a href="/wiki/.uz" title=".uz">.uz</a>, online at <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="https://uz./">https://uz./</a> (as a mirror of <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="https://cctld.uz/">https://cctld.uz/</a>, albeit with an invalid certificate). Other ccTLDs with A or AAAA records, as of August 2021, include: <a href="/wiki/.bh" title=".bh">.bh</a>, <a href="/wiki/.cm" title=".cm">.cm</a>, <a href="/wiki/.pn" title=".pn">.pn</a>, <a href="/wiki/.tk" title=".tk">.tk</a>, <a href="/wiki/.va" title=".va">.va</a>, and <a href="/wiki/.ws" title=".ws">.ws</a>.
</p><p>A similar query to <i>org</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">&#39;</span>s presented above can be made for <i>ai</i>, which shows A and MX records for the TLD:
</p>
<pre style="font-size:85%">QUESTION
ai. IN ANY
ANSWER
ai. 21599 IN A  209.59.119.34
ai. 21599 IN MX 10 mail.offshore.ai.
ai. 21599 IN NS anycastdns1-cz.nic.ai.
ai. 21599 IN NS anycastdns2-cz.nic.ai.
ai. 21599 IN NS pch.whois.ai.
[…]
</pre>
<p>Historically, many other ccTLDs have had A or AAAA records. On 3 September 2013, as reported by the <a href="/wiki/IETF" class="mw-redirect" title="IETF">IETF</a>, they were the following:<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/.ac" title=".ac">.ac</a>, <a href="/wiki/.dk" title=".dk">.dk</a>, <a href="/wiki/.gg" title=".gg">.gg</a>, <a href="/wiki/.io" title=".io">.io</a>, <a href="/wiki/.je" title=".je">.je</a>, <a href="/wiki/.kh" title=".kh">.kh</a>, <a href="/wiki/.sh" title=".sh">.sh</a>, <a href="/wiki/.tm" title=".tm">.tm</a>, <a href="/wiki/.to" title=".to">.to</a>, and <a href="/wiki/.vi" title=".vi">.vi</a>.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="New_TLDs">New TLDs</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: New TLDs">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Following a 2014 resolution by ICANN, newly registered TLDs must implement the following A, MX, TXT, and SRV apex DNS records – where <code>&lt;TLD&gt;</code> stands for the registered TLD – for at least 90 days:<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<pre style="font-size:85%">&lt;TLD&gt;. 3600 IN MX  10      your-dns-needs-immediate-attention.&lt;TLD&gt;.
&lt;TLD&gt;. 3600 IN SRV 10 10 0 your-dns-needs-immediate-attention.&lt;TLD&gt;.
&lt;TLD&gt;. 3600 IN TXT         "Your DNS configuration needs immediate attention see https://icann.org/namecollision"
&lt;TLD&gt;. 3600 IN A           127.0.53.53
</pre>
<p>This requirement is meant to avoid domain name collisions when new TLDs are registered. For example, programmers may have used custom local domains such as <i>foo.bar</i> or <i>test.dev</i>, which would both collide with the creation of gTLDs <a href="/wiki/.bar" title=".bar">.bar</a> in 2014 and <a href="/wiki/.dev" title=".dev">.dev</a> in 2019. As of August 2021, top-level domains with these special apex records are <a href="/w/index.php?title=.arab&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title=".arab (page does not exist)">.arab</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=.cpa&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title=".cpa (page does not exist)">.cpa</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=.politie&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title=".politie (page does not exist)">.politie</a>, and <a href="/w/index.php?title=.watches&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title=".watches (page does not exist)">.watches</a>.
</p><p>While this does create apex DNS records of type A and MX, they do not qualify as a dotless domain, as the records should not point to real servers. For instance, the A record contains the IP 127.0.53.53, a loopback address (see <a href="/wiki/IPv4#Addressing" title="IPv4">IPv4 § Addressing</a>), picked as a mnemonic to indicate a DNS-related problem, as <a href="/wiki/List_of_TCP_and_UDP_port_numbers" title="List of TCP and UDP port numbers">DNS uses port 53</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Pseudo-domains">Pseudo-domains</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Pseudo-domains">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Pseudo-top-level_domain" title="Pseudo-top-level domain">Pseudo-top-level domain</a></div>
<table class="box-More_citations_needed plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td class="mbox-image"><div style="width:52px"><a href="/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png" decoding="async" width="50" height="39" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="399" /></a></div></td><td class="mbox-text"><div class="mbox-text-span">This section <b>needs additional citations for <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability">verification</a></b>.<span class="hide-when-compact"> Please help <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit">improve this article</a> by <a href="/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners" title="Help:Referencing for beginners">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.<br /><small><span class="plainlinks"><i>Find sources:</i>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?as_eq=wikipedia&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22">"Top-level domain"</a>&#160;–&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbm=nws&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22+-wikipedia&amp;tbs=ar:1">news</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22&amp;tbs=bkt:s&amp;tbm=bks">newspapers</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbs=bks:1&amp;q=%22Top-level+domain%22+-wikipedia">books</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22Top-level+domain%22">scholar</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Top-level+domain%22&amp;acc=on&amp;wc=on">JSTOR</a></span></small></span>  <span class="date-container"><i>(<span class="date">December 2018</span>)</i></span><span class="hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a href="/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title="Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Several networks, such as <a href="/wiki/BITNET" title="BITNET">BITNET</a>, <a href="/wiki/CSNET" title="CSNET">CSNET</a>, and <a href="/wiki/UUCP" title="UUCP">UUCP</a>, existed that were in widespread use among computer professionals and academic users, but were not interoperable directly with the Internet and exchanged mail with the Internet via special email gateways. For relaying purposes on the gateways, messages associated with these networks were labeled with suffixes such as <a href="/wiki/.bitnet" class="mw-redirect" title=".bitnet">bitnet</a>, <a href="/wiki/.oz" class="mw-redirect" title=".oz">oz</a>, <a href="/wiki/.csnet" class="mw-redirect" title=".csnet">csnet</a>, or <a href="/wiki/.uucp" class="mw-redirect" title=".uucp">uucp</a>, but these domains did not exist as top-level domains in the public <a href="/wiki/Domain_Name_System" title="Domain Name System">Domain Name System</a> of the Internet.
</p><p>Most of these networks have long since ceased to exist, and although UUCP still gets significant use in parts of the world where Internet infrastructure has not yet become well established, it subsequently transitioned to using Internet domain names, and pseudo-domains now largely survive as historical relics.  One notable exception is the 2007 emergence of <a href="/wiki/Society_for_Worldwide_Interbank_Financial_Telecommunication" class="mw-redirect" title="Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication">SWIFTNet</a> Mail, which uses the swift pseudo-domain.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The anonymity network <a href="/wiki/Tor_(network)" title="Tor (network)">Tor</a> formerly used the top-level pseudo-domain <a href="/wiki/.onion" title=".onion">onion</a> for <a href="/wiki/Tor_hidden_service" class="mw-redirect" title="Tor hidden service">Tor hidden services</a>, which can only be reached with a Tor client because it uses the Tor <a href="/wiki/Onion_routing" title="Onion routing">onion routing</a> protocol to reach the hidden service to protect the anonymity of users. However, the pseudo-domain became officially reserved in October 2015.   <a href="/wiki/I2p" class="mw-redirect" title="I2p">i2p</a> provides a similar hidden pseudo-domain, .i2p.
</p><p><a href="/wiki/British_Telecom" class="mw-redirect" title="British Telecom">BT</a> hubs use the top-level pseudo-domain home for local DNS resolution of routers, modems and gateways.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Further_reading">Further reading</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Further reading">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul><li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20040124074709/http://www.addressingtheworld.info/"><i>Addressing the World</i></a>: <i>National Identity and Internet Country Code Domains</i>, edited by Erica Schlesinger Wass (Rowman &amp; Littlefield, 2003, <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1067248974"/><a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-7425-2810-3" title="Special:BookSources/0-7425-2810-3">0-7425-2810-3</a>) examines connections between cultures and their ccTLDs.</li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/ruling-root"><i>Ruling the Root</i></a> by Milton Mueller (MIT Press, 2001, <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1067248974"/><a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-262-13412-8" title="Special:BookSources/0-262-13412-8">0-262-13412-8</a>) discusses TLDs and domain name policy more generally.</li></ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="External_links">External links</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Top-level_domain&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: External links">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<table role="presentation" class="mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox" style="background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000">
<tbody><tr>

<td class="mbox-text plainlist">Wikimedia Commons has media related to <span style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;"><a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Top-level_domains" class="extiw" title="commons:Category:Top-level domains">Top-level domains</a></span>.</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<table role="presentation" class="mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox" style="background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000">
<tbody><tr>
<td class="mbox-image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Wikidata-logo.svg/40px-Wikidata-logo.svg.png" decoding="async" width="40" height="22" class="noviewer" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Wikidata-logo.svg/60px-Wikidata-logo.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Wikidata-logo.svg/80px-Wikidata-logo.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1050" data-file-height="590" /></td>
<td class="mbox-text plainlist"><a href="/wiki/Wikidata" title="Wikidata">Wikidata</a> has the property: 
<ul><li><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Disc_Plain_blue_dark.svg/4px-Disc_Plain_blue_dark.svg.png" decoding="async" width="4" height="4" style="vertical-align: middle" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Disc_Plain_blue_dark.svg/6px-Disc_Plain_blue_dark.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Disc_Plain_blue_dark.svg/8px-Disc_Plain_blue_dark.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="460" data-file-height="460" /> <b><i><a href="https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Property_talk:P78" class="extiw" title="d:Property talk:P78">top-level Internet domain (P78)</a></i></b> (see <span class="plainlinks"><a class="external text" href="https://query.wikidata.org/embed.html#SELECT%20%3FWikiData_item_%20%3FWikiData_item_Label%20%3Fvalue%20%3FvalueLabel%20%3FEnglish_WikiPedia_article%20%23Show%20data%20in%20this%20order%0A%7B%0A%09%3FWikiData_item_%20wdt%3AP78%20%3Fvalue%20.%20%23Collecting%20all%20items%20which%20have%20P78%20data%2C%20from%20whole%20WikiData%20item%20pages%0A%09OPTIONAL%20%7B%3FEnglish_WikiPedia_article%20schema%3Aabout%20%3FWikiData_item_%3B%20schema%3AisPartOf%20%3Chttps%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2F%3E%20.%7D%20%23If%20collected%20item%20has%20link%20to%20English%20WikiPedia%2C%20show%20that%0A%09SERVICE%20wikibase%3Alabel%20%7B%20bd%3AserviceParam%20wikibase%3Alanguage%20%22en%22%20%20%7D%20%23Show%20label%20in%20this%20language.%20%22en%22%20is%20English.%20%20%20%0A%7D%0ALIMIT%201000">uses</a></span>)</li></ul></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
